I now have everything I need. Here is the complete diagnosis, root cause, fix, and architectural principle.

---

## Diagnosis

There are **three interlocking bugs** in `src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`, all caused by the same structural flaw: the hover-emphasis system lives inside the Mesh-specific branch of what should be a single, unconditional code path.

### Bug 1 — Link emphasis (`linkColor`, `linkWidth`) is view-conditional

Reading the constants block, the component defines a full two-tier emphasis system:

```
LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH / LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE_WIDTH   → emphasized (connected)
LINK_COLOR_DIM / LINK_WIDTH_DIM                  → dimmed (not connected)
TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW / TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE  → Pathway/Signal emphasized
LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW / LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE  → Pathway/Signal emphasized
```

But the `linkColor` and `linkWidth` callbacks passed to `ForceGraph2D` only consult `hoveredNodeId` when `viewMode === "mesh"`. The Pathway and Signal branches return `TERRA_LINK` / `LUMEN_LINK` (the resting colors) unconditionally, so hover produces no visible link change in those modes.

### Bug 2 — Node emphasis (`nodeColor`) is also view-gated

The same conditional structure applies to node rendering: only Mesh consults `hoveredNodeId` to modulate opacity/brightness. In Pathway and Signal, the per-node brightness returned by `getNodeColor` is always the hierarchy-derived resting value, so the hovered node appears to light up differently (it gets the generic `nodeColor` prop callback result rather than the emphasis-boosted value).

### Bug 3 — Particle emission ignores `hoveredNodeId` scope

`linkDirectionalParticleWidth` (Signal view) fires on every link in the active path, regardless of whether a hover is active. The hover state is never consulted. When the user hovers a node that is *not* the current active source, particles should either:
- Restrict to only the hovered node's connected links (preview mode), or  
- Stop entirely on non-connected links and continue only on connected ones.

Currently the wave-emission loop doesn't receive the hover set at all.

---

## Root Cause

**EAP-125** — *Per-view callback divergence: a multi-mode component implements its interaction model as N separate view-gated code paths instead of a single canonical pipeline.* The hover-emphasis pipeline (`connectedLinkSet` → dim/emphasize split → node opacity boost → particle scope) was implemented once for Mesh, then the Pathway and Signal branches were bolted on independently without threading the same hover state through them. Each time a new view was added (ENG-236 Signal BFS, ENG-237 emphasis system), the emphasis logic was either omitted or re-implemented shallowly, causing the views to drift.

The secondary anti-pattern is **EAP-113** *(Verification by Grep-for-Expected-Rule Without Behavioral Check)*: the constants `LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH`, `TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW`, etc. exist and look correct when grepped, which masks that they are never reached on three of four code paths.

---

## Fix

All changes are in **`src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`** only. The playground page is documentation and does not change (Intent Gate: this is a component-visual fix → edit `src/`, never the playground page).

### Step 1 — Promote `hoveredNodeId` and `connectedLinkSet` to unconditional top-level state

Ensure both are computed in the component body unconditionally (they almost certainly already are as `useRef`/`useState`), and that `connectedLinkSet` is always populated whenever `hoveredNodeId` is non-null.

```tsx
// ── Hover state (view-mode-independent) ─────────────────────────────────────
// These refs are read by all three link/node/particle callbacks below.
// They must NEVER be scoped inside a viewMode conditional.
const hoveredNodeIdRef = useRef<string | null>(null);
const connectedLinkSetRef = useRef<Set<ForceGraphLink>>(new Set());

const handleNodeHover = useCallback(
  (node: ForceGraphNode | null) => {
    hoveredNodeIdRef.current = node?.id ?? null;

    if (node) {
      // Rebuild connected set for every view mode identically
      const connected = new Set<ForceGraphLink>();
      for (const link of links) {
        const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
        const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
        if (srcId === node.id || tgtId === node.id) {
          connected.add(link);
        }
      }
      connectedLinkSetRef.current = connected;
    } else {
      connectedLinkSetRef.current = new Set();
    }

    onNodeHover?.(node);
  },
  [links, onNodeHover],
);
```

### Step 2 — Unify `linkColor` into a single function that dispatches on both `viewMode` AND hover state

Replace any `viewMode === "mesh" ? hoveredColor : restingColor` pattern with a single `getLinkColor(link, viewMode, hoveredNodeId, connectedLinkSet)` helper:

```tsx
// ── Unified link color — single source of truth for ALL view modes ───────────
// Rule: when hoveredNodeId is set, connected links emphasize, all others dim.
// This applies identically in Mesh, Pathway, and Signal.
function getUnifiedLinkColor(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
  hoveredNodeId: string | null,
  connectedLinkSet: Set<ForceGraphLink>,
): string {
  const isBi = link.bidirectional ?? false;

  // ── No hover active: return resting color for this mode ──────────────────
  if (!hoveredNodeId) {
    if (viewMode === "mesh") return LINK_COLOR;
    if (viewMode === "signal") {
      // Signal resting state is handled by the particle + active-path system;
      // link color itself stays at SIGNAL_ACTIVE / SIGNAL_PREVIEW.
      return isBi ? SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK;
    }
    // Pathway resting
    return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
  }

  // ── Hover active ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  const isConnected = connectedLinkSet.has(link);

  if (!isConnected) {
    // Dim regardless of view mode
    return LINK_COLOR_DIM;
  }

  // Emphasized — use the semantic color for the view mode
  if (viewMode === "mesh") {
    // Mesh: glow pass color (the canvas overlay draws the core separately)
    return `rgba(160, 160, 160, 0.45)`;
  }
  // Pathway + Signal: preserve semantic color, boost opacity
  return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
}

// ── Unified link width ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function getUnifiedLinkWidth(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
  hoveredNodeId: string | null,
  connectedLinkSet: Set<ForceGraphLink>,
): number {
  if (!hoveredNodeId) {
    if (viewMode === "pathway") {
      return 0.4 + (link.confidence ?? 0.5) * 1.6; // confidence-scaled, unchanged
    }
    return LINK_WIDTH;
  }

  const isConnected = connectedLinkSet.has(link);
  if (!isConnected) return LINK_WIDTH_DIM;

  // All three views use the same emphasis width on hover
  if (viewMode === "pathway") {
    // Pathway keeps its confidence scaling but boosts it
    return (0.4 + (link.confidence ?? 0.5) * 1.6) * 2.5;
  }
  return LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH;
}
```

Then the props passed to `<ForceGraph2D>` become:

```tsx
linkColor={(link) =>
  getUnifiedLinkColor(
    link as ForceGraphLink,
    viewMode ?? "mesh",
    hoveredNodeIdRef.current,
    connectedLinkSetRef.current,
  )
}
linkWidth={(link) =>
  getUnifiedLinkWidth(
    link as ForceGraphLink,
    viewMode ?? "mesh",
    hoveredNodeIdRef.current,
    connectedLinkSetRef.current,
  )
}
```

### Step 3 — Unify `nodeColor` so hover-emphasis applies in all views

The `nodeCanvasObject` callback already draws nodes. Add a single `isEmphasized / isDimmed` gate at the top of the node-paint block, based on `hoveredNodeIdRef`, and apply it unconditionally before the view-mode-specific draw calls:

```tsx
// Inside nodeCanvasObject (or the nodeColor prop, whichever path the
// component currently uses for colour resolution):
const hovered = hoveredNodeIdRef.current;
const nodeId = node.id;

const emphasisState: "emphasized" | "dimmed" | "neutral" =
  !hovered
    ? "neutral"
    : nodeId === hovered
      ? "emphasized"
      : connectedLinkSetRef.current.size > 0 &&
          [...connectedLinkSetRef.current].some(
            (l) =>
              getLinkNodeId(l.source) === nodeId ||
              getLinkNodeId(l.target) === nodeId,
          )
        ? "neutral"   // direct neighbor: not dimmed, not boosted
        : "dimmed";

// Apply before any view-mode-specific paint:
const emphasisAlphaMultiplier =
  emphasisState === "emphasized" ? 1.35
  : emphasisState === "dimmed"   ? 0.18
  : 1.0;
```

Wrap every `ctx.globalAlpha = baseAlpha` assignment inside the node painter with `baseAlpha * emphasisAlphaMultiplier`. Do **not** fork on `viewMode` here — the multiplier is the same for all three.

### Step 4 — Scope particle emission to connected links during hover

In the wave-emission rAF loop (the block that calls `emitParticle` or sets `linkDirectionalParticleWidth`), add a connected-link gate:

```tsx
// Inside the per-link emission decision in the rAF/signal loop:
const hovered = hoveredNodeIdRef.current;
const isOnConnectedPath =
  !hovered || connectedLinkSetRef.current.has(link);

if (!isOnConnectedPath) {
  // Particle suppression: skip emission for this link while hover is active
  continue; // or: return 0 for linkDirectionalParticleWidth
}

// ... existing wave probability / BFS / emitParticle logic unchanged ...
```

This is a **gate**, not a replacement — the existing BFS path-scoping from ENG-236 stays in place. Hover adds a second, outer scope on top of it: active-path BFS first, then hover-connected filter second.

---

## Architectural Rule (so this never drifts again)

> **Every `ForceGraph2D` callback prop that expresses a visual interaction state — `linkColor`, `linkWidth`, `nodeColor`/`nodeCanvasObject`, and `linkDirectionalParticleWidth` — MUST be computed by a single mode-agnostic helper function that receives `(entity, viewMode, hoverState)` as arguments. `viewMode` controls _what the resting appearance is_; `hoverState` controls _the emphasis/dim delta on top of that_. These are orthogonal concerns and must be layered, never branched.**

In practice this means:

1. **No `if (viewMode === "mesh") { hoverLogic } else { /* no hover */ }` constructs.** Hover logic is never inside a `viewMode` branch — it wraps around the view-mode switch or is applied as a multiplier after it.

2. **`hoveredNodeIdRef` and `connectedLinkSetRef` are unconditional component-level refs.** They are always populated by `onNodeHover`. No view mode is allowed to skip that handler or short-circuit the set rebuild.

3. **Particles obey the same connected-link gate as link colors.** If a link would be dimmed in color, its particles are also suppressed. The two systems share the same `connectedLinkSetRef` — no separate hover tracking for particles.

4. **When a new view mode is added**, the single helper functions pick up hover behavior for free because hover is handled in the caller layer, above the view-mode dispatch.

This is the same principle that governs the node brightness system (ENG-239/ENG-240): hierarchy-derived brightness is computed once, then emphasis delta is applied on top. Hover emphasis is the interaction-state equivalent of that pattern.

